<doc docid="XIN_CMN_20060206.0133" genre="newswire" sysid="chg">
<p>
<seg id="1"> (Overseas Affairs about China) Third Chinese Countryman Robbed and Killed within Two Days in South Africa </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="2"> Xinhua News Agency, Johannesburg, February 6 (reporter: Chen Ming) Lin Yixing, an overseas Chinese from Fuqing, Fujian Province, China, was wounded when he was running his bar, and was robbed by local gunmen in the early morning of February 5, South African local time. He died after unsuccessful emergency treatment at a hospital in Bloemfontein, the judicial capital of South Africa, in the early morning of the 6th. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3"> As Feng Yang, the President of the Overseas Chinese Association of Freedom State Province, said, the incident occurred at a bar in Welkom, more that 130 kilometers northwest of Bloemfontein. </seg>
<seg id="4"> While Lin Yixing, the bar owner, was cleaning items under the bar counter and preparing to end that day's business, </seg>
<seg id="5"> there were still three customers at the bar at that time. One of them pulled out a pistol and rushed behind the bar to rob him. </seg>
<seg id="6"> Lin Yixing, who was more than 40 years old, wrestled with those robbers. They shot Ling Yixing one time, and then fled. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="7"> Locals rushed to the scene after they heard the news, and sent Lin Yixing to the hospital for emergency treatment. Since Lin Yixing's body had "symptoms of diffuse capillary bleeding," and the bleeding could not be stopped, Lin died around 3:30 a.m. in the early morning of February 6. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="8"> Xu Defu and Wu Gang, the two consuls from China's General Consulate in Johannesburg, and Lin Changming, the Vice President of China's Fujian Townsmen Association in South Africa, drove to Bloemfontein on February 6, and assisted family members of the dead with handling the subsequent affairs. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="9"> Lin Yixing becomes the third Chinese to be killed by a robber's gunshot within 36 hours, and the fourth Chinese to have died in South Africa this year. </seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="XIN_CMN_20060206.0192" genre="newswire" sysid="chg">
<p>
<seg id="1"> (Newspaper Digest) Part-Time Workers and High School Graduates Become Major Forces of Hourly-Paid Work in Shanghai </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="2"> Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, February 7. The "Guidance on the Current Standard for Hourly-Paid Wages in 2006" issued by the Labor and Social Support Bureau of Shanghai City on February 6, lists 120 occupations, which is 11 more than the number issued last time. The "wage levels" of the original positions are either increased or reduced. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3"> As an estimate made by related experts of the Labor and Social Support Bureau of Shanghai City, currently the hourly-paid workers in Shanghai are more than one million. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="4"> As China Youth Journal reported, part-time workers and high school graduates are the major part of the team of hourly-paid labors. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5"> Through a direct survey of more than 8,000 hourly-paid workers, more than half of them are part-time workers, and their ratio is 51.1%. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="6"> Those part-time workers are generally well educated, and mainly do more technical work. For instance, the ratio of part-time workers in the translation occupation is as high as 81.7%, and that in the gym business is 61.6%. </seg>
<seg id="7"> High income is one of the important reasons for many people to work at hourly-paid part-time jobs. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="8"> As was learned, monthly income for some positions can reach up to several tens of thousands of Yuan, and it is difficult to find high-demand talents, such as simultaneous interpreters; most hourly-paid workers' monthly incomes can reach more than 2,000 Yuan, such as part-time financial workers, wedding ceremony managers, etc. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="9"> One of the important reasons for the popularity of part-time workers for hourly wages is that those jobs suit individual interests and workers can learn more knowledge from those jobs. </seg>
<seg id="10"> For instance, Mr. Gu, who is a manager of the Human Resources Unit at a company, uses several hours to handle business accounts for a foreign business agency every week. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Mr. Gu thinks that the greatest benefit of a part-time job is to continuously renew his own knowledge, and has opportunities to know another field, and of course, a monthly income of 2,000 Yuan is also attractive to a certain extent. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="12"> Since some positions for hourly-paid workers are low-skill ones, and their working patterns are flexible and free, they have gradually become popular among a lot of graduates who are looking for jobs. 14% of hourly-paid workers are graduates from colleges and polytechnic schools in the last three years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="13"> "I did not want to do an hourly-paid job in the beginning. But several months later, I feel it is better than 9 to 5 work." </seg>
<seg id="14"> Xiao Huang's job hunting is not that satisfying after he graduates from college. He eventually registers with a hotel and plays background music on a piano. </seg>
<seg id="15"> "I am quite satisfied with my current work, 100 yuan per hour, and the environment is also good. What I should do now is to find several more hourly-paid jobs." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="16"> As has been learned, hourly-paid jobs have become an important path for those graduates who are looking for jobs to accumulate work experience, exercise their work skills, improve their communication skills, and enrich their social experience. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="17"> Those graduates who work at hourly-paid jobs are mainly concentrated in positions that require more knowledge and skills, including translation positions, which require professional skills, and entertainment and performance positions, which require current popularity. These two kinds of positions are 22.1% and 26.8%, respectively, among those jobs that require more knowledge and skills. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="18"> Some positions for hourly-paid workers do not require high skills, such as food promotion workers, merchandise handlers, and unemployed workers who are able to work through simple trainings. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Data shows that those hourly-paid workers who used to be unemployed are 39% of the total hourly-paid workers; among them, workers who used to work in retail business are 68.4%; and those in restaurants and food businesses are 58.7%. The hourly-paid jobs have become an important channel for unemployed workers to find their employment. </seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="XIN_CMN_20060208.0094" genre="newswire" sysid="chg">
