<p>
<seg id="1"> Two Light Aircrafts Crashed in New Zealand </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="2"> Xinhua News Agency, Wellington, February 9. Two New Zealand light planes crashed in the sky over the Shannon area about 100 kilometers north of the capital, Wellington, on February 9, and two flight school students died in the planes. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3"> As a person responsible for the local civil aviation department said, both of the pilots in the planes were students of the flight school at Massey University, who were still in training and had not earned their flight licenses. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The two planes were flying in an uncontrolled airspace when the accident occurred. Pilots who fly in this kind of airspace should be responsible for the navigation and safety conditions of their planes, according to regulations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5"> An eyewitness at the site where the accident occurred told New Zealand media that he heard a big explosion when the planes crashed, and saw the planes falling quickly to the ground. </seg>
<seg id="6"> Another eyewitness also confirmed that he heard a big explosion before the planes fell to the ground, and saw falling pieces of the planes. </seg>
</p>
