<doc docid="XIN_CMN_20060217.0193" genre="newswire" sysid="chg">
<p>
<seg id="1"> (Winter Olympic Games: Stimulant) News Analysis: Pyleva Incident Might Be Settled by Leaving it Unsettled </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="2"> Xinhua News Agency, Turin, February 17. News Analysis: Pyleva Incident Might Be Settled by Leaving it Unsettled </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3"> Xinhua News Agency Reporters: Gao Peng, Ding Ying </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="4"> Although Italy reiterated that any athletes who are discovered using stimulants may face the "disaster of being jailed," many cases currently demonstrate that it is unlikely to happen to Russian women's biathlon athlete Olga Pyleva, who is at the center of the first scandal over stimulant use at the Winter Olympic Games. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5"> The first stimulant use scandal at the Turin Winter Olympic Games was exposed on the 16th, and Olga Pyleva was discovered to have used the illegal and banned drug carphedon. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The next day, the International Olympic Committee announced that Pyleva had been thrown out of the Winter Olympic Games, and the silver medal she won for the 15 km women's biathlon had been withdrawn. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The same day, the International Winter Biathlon Alliance determined to forbid Pyleva to participate in the sport for two years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="8"> The International Olympic Committee has been implementing the regulation that once athletes are discovered using stimulants, they will lose their qualification to participate in the Games, and the scores they achieved will be withdrawn, but they are not subject to legal punishment. </seg>
<seg id="9"> However, according to Italian law, the carrying and use of stimulants by any athlete are criminal activities. A law enforcement organization has the right to directly arrest and investigate any athlete who uses stimulants. Any violators of the law are subject to jail for 3 months to 3 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="10"> The International Olympic Committee had been "bargaining" with the Italian government for one year, and eventually reached an agreement last December. Both sides agreed that during the period of the Winter Olympic Games, any athletes who use stimulants would be handled according to Italian laws. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="11"> Through the unremitting efforts made by the International Olympic Committee, the Italian side made a compromise four days before the opening ceremonies of the Winter Olympic Games, and promised that the police would not enter the Olympic Village to search athlete residences during the Olympic Games. But any athletes whose drug tests show positive will be investigated by Italian prosecution organizations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="12"> Some reports said that Pescante, an official of the Italian government responsible for supervision of the Turin Winter Olympic Games, has transferred Pyleva's stimulant case to a Turin prosecution organization. </seg>
<seg id="13"> However, the International Olympic Committee and Pescante himself have not confirmed this so far. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="14"> Andrey Dmytriev, a doctor for the Russian Biathlon Team ,disclosed at noontime on the 17th that Pyleva had left Turin and returned home. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="15"> Shi Kangcheng, a Chinese sports official who had been in a position at the World Anti-Stimulant Organization for many years, thinks that once Pyleva returns home, this case might eventually "be settled by leaving it unsettled." </seg>
<seg id="16"> Shi Kangcheng said that the International Olympic Committee and the Italian government have not "completely addressed" the anti-stimulant issue at the Winter Olympic Games, and it is hard to say what the outcome would be even if Italian prosecution organizations really did get involved in the case. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="17"> Based on past penalty cases in which Italy sentenced or punished its own athletes who used stimulants, the most serious penalty was merely a "two-year probation." </seg>
<seg id="18"> Thus, senior reporter Piali from the Italian ANSA said that the possibility of Pyleva being jailed is "very small," and at most, she might be fined. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="19"> Piali also said that although an Italian court could sentence her by default, it is impossible for the Italian police to catch Pyleva abroad and bring her back to serve the sentence. </seg>
<seg id="20"> If Pyleva refuses to accept the sentence, the Italian side can do nothing about it. </seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="XIN_CMN_20060218.0001" genre="newswire" sysid="chg">
<p>
<seg id="1"> Comprehensive News: New Epidemic Spots Continuously Emerge; Every Country in the World Taking Strict Prevention Measures </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="2"> Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, February 18. A comprehensive report by Xinhua News Agency reporters abroad: Bird flu is further spread on the African continent. </seg>
<seg id="3"> The World Health Organization confirmed on the 17th that birds have been found dead of infections by the bird flu virus in three areas of Egypt. </seg>
<seg id="4"> In Europe, France also first discovered the H5 bird flu virus; Europe and Africa are on high alert and strengthening prevention measures against the epidemic. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5"> Hussein Bushila, a consultant for the Eastern Mediterranean region of the WHO, told press in Egypt on the 17th that three areas in Egypt - including Cairo and Jizah in the central region, and Minya in the southern region - have found birds dead of H5N1 bird flu virus infection; Egyptian government departments have started to kill poultries suspected of being infected with bird flu. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="6"> Experts pointed out that Egypt is an important passage for migrant birds in the Middle East and North Africa. The possibility of migrant birds bringing bird flu virus across borders is very high. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Egypt has announced a ban on import of any live poultries from foreign countries, and strengthened quarantine work at border ports. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="8"> More than 800 chickens died of unknown causes on a chicken farm in the capital of Cameroon, Yaounde, in the past week. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Cameroon has decided to immediately suspend imports of all poultries and pork from Nigeria, where the bird flu epidemic was discovered, and discontinued trade of poultries and related products in markets in border areas between the two countries. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The Cameroonian government has also established a monitoring and detection network that can cover its overall territories for epidemic detection. Its Bayside Center and the State Veterinary Laboratory are also under an emergency status so that they can deploy any test work associated with the H5N1 virus at any time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="11"> In Europe, Denmark and Sweden initially excluded the epidemic on the 17th. </seg>
<seg id="12"> The Swedish Veterinary Institute issued a test result that shows the dead swans found in Sweden this Wednesday were not infected with the bird flu virus. </seg>
<seg id="13"> An initial test result done by the Danish State Veterinary Control Bureau also showed that the 30 dead swans found in Danish territories in recent days were not infected with the bird flu virus. </seg>
<seg id="14"> But an agricultural department stated that Denmark still cannot lower its guard. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="15"> 9 bird flu epidemic spots have been discovered in Romania in Eastern Europe this year. WHO experts in Bucharest said on the 17th that bird flu has spread to almost every area of the Delta Region of the Danube River, and the situation must be carefully coped with, and Romania might be continuously threatened by bird flu within 3 to 5 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="16"> In Bangladesh in Asia, the government has taken every measure necessary to prevent bird flu. </seg>
<seg id="17"> The government's Poultry Service Bureau has provided related officials books about prevention of bird flu, and also simultaneously organized poultry raisers for trainings. </seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="XIN_CMN_20060218.0022" genre="newswire" sysid="chg">
<p>
<seg id="1"> (Newspaper Digest) China's First Blood Sharing Information Management System Established in Zhejiang </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="2"> Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, February 18. As the Blood Center of Zhejiang Province disclosed, China's first blood sharing information data management and control network system has recently been formally established at the center and has been put into operation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3"> A leader involved with the Blood Center of Zhejiang Province said that this means that any citizen who has freely donated his blood in any county (city, district) blood collection and supply institutions of Zhejiang Province will have a unique code record. When he donates blood again, information that determines if he is qualified to donate his blood will immediately show up as long as his code record, individual information, blood type, blood donation record, and time of last blood donation are entered. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="4"> The leader further explained that if the system shows a free-blood donor is still within an interval period through entering the related code records, it will point out that the person does not meet the requirements for blood donation at this time. </seg>
<seg id="5"> In this way it can protect not only the health of the blood donor, but also the health and safety of blood recipients. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="6"> In addition, when the blood supply is in shortage, a blood donor or his relatives can have the right to use his blood first. As long as you enter a valid I.D. for the blood donor, his related information will show up, which is pretty convenient. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="7"> As Today's Morning Journal of Hangzhou reported, the information system has currently been put into operation in 36 blood collection and supply institutions throughout the province. And the blood resources status for all of the blood collection and supply institutions in the province can also be shown in real time, which has accomplished data sharing throughout the province. </seg>
</p>
</doc>
