<seg id="39"> Er, yes, host. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Er, according to what I have learned from the Chinese consulate general in Karachi, er, the Chinese embassy and consulate has already informed the victims' work unit of this tragic incident. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Well, according to the general practice, um, the work unit of the victims should be consulting with the families before making any final decision as to how to deal with the aftermath. </seg>
<seg id="42"> In addition, the Pakistani Foreign Ministry also issued a statement yesterday. </seg>
<seg id="43"> He, er, the statement indicated that the perpetuators of the incident attempted to sow discord in the relations between China and Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="44"> Er, the statement said that there will be a thorough investigation into the incident and that Pakistan will strengthen security protection of all Chinese working in this country.  In addition, it said that Pakistan will try all it can to prevent similar incidents from reoccurring. </seg>
<seg id="45"> Er, in addition, according to the report by Pakistan's private-run GEO on the evening of the 15th, Bashir, chief executive officer of the Attock cement factory in Pakistan, said in his interview with the station this evening that following the attack, the Pakistani side will try to arrange for the remaining 11 Chinese engineering and technical personnel working on the construction site of the cement project to return to their country as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id="46"> Well, um, Bashir also said in the interview that with regard to the question of some Pakistani media why the Chinese engineers did not have security guards with them when the incident took place, er, he said, er, actually the cement factory where these engineers worked has its own security system; however, since the incident occurred within the boundary of the factory, none of security guards were with them at the time. </seg>
<seg id="47"> Well, he expressed deep regrets about the occurrence of this tragic incident. </seg>
<seg id="48"> Host. </seg>
<seg id="49"> Eh, all right. </seg>
<seg id="50"> Er, besides, it is actually not the first time that Chinese engineering personnel were killed in attacks in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="51"> Such an incident occurred in October 2004. </seg>
<seg id="52"> Two Chinese engineers were kidnapped by an armed group in South Waziristan. </seg>
<seg id="53"> In the end, one of them unfortunately died during the rescue mission. </seg>
<seg id="54"> In addition, three engineering personnel also died in a bombing attack in Gwadar in May of the same year. </seg>
<seg id="55"> Let's have a recap. </seg>
<seg id="56"> On May 3, 2004, in the port of Gwadar in the southern part of the province of Balochistan, Pakistan, a vehicle carrying 12 Chinese was hit by a car bomb while it was driving to the port construction site. </seg>
<seg id="57"> In the end three Chinese engineering personnel died, while nine people were wounded. </seg>
<seg id="58"> This attack was believed to be launched by local separatists and tribal militias. </seg>
<seg id="59"> On October 9 of the same year, two Chinese engineers were kidnapped by gunmen in South Waziristan where Pakistan borders Afghanistan. </seg>
<seg id="60"> When Pakistani troops came to the rescue of the hostages later, one engineer was unfortunately shot to death. </seg>
<seg id="61"> However, armed groups linked with al-Qaeda rather than separatist militants were believed to be responsible for this hostage incident. </seg>
<seg id="62"> Since China has a close economic exchange with Pakistan and participates in Pakistan's infrastructure construction, quite a number of Chinese engineering personnel are working there. </seg>
<seg id="63"> Yet, tribal militias in Pakistan accused the government of robbing them of their natural resources. </seg>
<seg id="64"> Consequently, Chinese people have fallen victims several times to attacks and abductions. </seg>
<seg id="65"> This comprehensive report has been brought to you by Phoenix Satellite V. </seg>
