<hl>
<seg id="1"> Joining Hands with Google in Battling Microsoft, Dell Charges Software Vendors "Shelving fees?" </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Yun Feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dell Inc. (US: DELL) and Google confirmed on Tuesday that Dell is testing personal computers that have installed Google Pack. </seg>
<seg id="4"> This move may pose a severe threat against Microsoft's (MSFT) dominant position in the PC software market. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Dell press spokesman Jess Blackburn indicated that the company is evaluating Google's software. </seg>
<seg id="6"> After installing this software, PC users can use the software to search the web as well as search for information stored on the PC. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Blackburn confirmed that at this time, the software being tested by the company include a Google-supported Dell homepage, Google Desktop Search, and Google Toolbar. </seg>
<seg id="8"> At the same time, Google press spokesman Jon Murchinson also confirmed that his company and Dell were testing a bundle of software developed by Google. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Earlier, the Wall Street Journal reported that IT upstart Google was in the process of negotiations with Dell and Hewlett-Packard Co., among others, in hopes of convincing these computer manufacturing giants to include Google software in their PCs. </seg>
<seg id="10"> According to insider sources quoted by the Wall Street Journal, Google may pay up to 1 billion US dollars to Dell over the next three years to achieve this goal. </seg>
<seg id="11"> However, the two companies did not reveal any of the relevant details. </seg>
<seg id="12"> In addition, Hewlett Packard refused to comment. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Microsoft press spokesman Neil Charney refused to comment on the above news. </seg>
<seg id="14"> As of now, Microsoft is planning to release its next-generation Windows operating system search tool and boost its development of web services. </seg>
<seg id="15"> On the day the news was released, Google's stock price again dropped by 4.46% to 367.92 US dollars. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Microsoft's stock price fell this day by 1%, closing at 26.94 US dollars. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Some analysts pointed out that Google is urgently seeking directions for growth outside of web search.  Joining hands with PC giants such as Dell may cause Google to threaten Microsoft's core business. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Matt Rosoff, an analyst from market research firm Directions on Microsoft, indicated that Google is in a rush to expand its revenue sources, which is definitely something Microsoft is concerned about. </seg>
<seg id="19"> However, some analysts are rather unimpressed. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Charles Di Bona, an analyst from market analysis firm Sanford C. Bernstein, pointed out that it is still too early for Google to shake Microsoft Windows' dominant position. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Reporter's note: Google Shaking Microsoft's Throne? </seg>
<seg id="22"> Huizhengyi </seg>
<seg id="23"> Computers have doubtlessly become a necessity for modern people in their life and work. </seg>
<seg id="24"> However, while everybody uses a computer skillfully, only a handful of people actually know the operating principle of a computer. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Just as using a "foolproof" camera, as long as the interface is friendly and software is easy to use, most beginners can equally feel comfortable operating such a black box as a computer. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Therefore, PC's manufacturer-installed original software will often determine the usage habits of most consumers. </seg>
<seg id="27"> It is exactly through this measure that Microsoft commands a solid control of the PC operating system market. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Now, Google, Microsoft's new rival, also intends to have its finger in the pie through this means. </seg>
<seg id="29"> A well-known economics media outfit recently used a very interesting metaphor for this. </seg>
<seg id="30"> "Dell, Hewlett Packard, and other computer manufacturers started to treat their computer products as supermarket shelves and charge software companies "shelving fees." </seg>
<seg id="31"> Winning bidders can have their software appear in the 'critical ten minutes' when users start their new computers so as to guide consumers to use their products. </seg>
<seg id="32"> This mode of charging fees resembles the way supermarkets charge food suppliers shelving fees." </seg>
<seg id="33"> Doubtlessly, this phenomenon indicates Microsoft's control is being loosened. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Microsoft's managers warned Bill Gates that if Google began to pay PC manufacturers to have their computers installed with Google software when they are shipped out, then Microsoft's hegemony will eventually be threatened. </seg>
<seg id="35"> No matter what will be the outcome of the situation, Microsoft's stable and easy days as number one may become history. </seg>
<seg id="36"> After all, it is easier to win the throne than to keep the throne. </seg>
<seg id="37"> There are no big events in the eyes of QuanDa, and all events in the world are commonplace events. </seg>
