<hl>
<seg id="1"> Xu Zhiyong: A Letter to Li Qun, Linyi Municipal Party Committee Secretary </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Fabuer </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Sender: sunnypku (sunny), </seg>
<seg id="4"> Forum: square </seg>
<seg id="5"> Subject: Xu Zhiyong: A Letter to Li Qun, Linyi Municipal Party Committee Secretary - Hooliganism May Also Harm Yourself </seg>
<seg id="6"> Mailing station: feel like old friends at the first meeting (Wed Feb 8 13:56:14 2006), this station (yjrg.net) </seg>
<seg id="7"> As of yesterday the Linyi government under your leadership had illegally put Chen Guangcheng under house arrest for 165 days. </seg>
<seg id="8"> You people have colluded with hooligans and underground society in taking illegal custody of a lawful blind citizen for a long time. </seg>
<seg id="9"> You people have cut off the phone line in his home and installed a cell phone interference device in his courtyard. </seg>
<seg id="10"> You people have also beat him and his family members several times. </seg>
<seg id="11"> You people's barbarism has exceeded the bottom line of a civilized society. </seg>
<seg id="12"> In early October 2005, you people acted like hooligans in the underground society and beat Attorney Li Fangping and me, but we put up with it, always trying our best to understand the difficulties you people are in.  We even acquiesced for some time after you people put Chen Guangcheng under house arrest. </seg>
<seg id="13"> However, 165 days have passed.  Instead of refraining yourself, you people even have become more unscrupulous. </seg>
<seg id="14"> You people dispatched regiments of police and hooligans to harass villagers. </seg>
<seg id="15"> You people continued to detain and beat villagers. </seg>
<seg id="16"> You people have gone too far! </seg>
<seg id="17"> Today, as you continue to organize hooligans in the underground society to hem in Chen Guangcheng, I remind you explicitly that acting as hooligans in the underground society may backfire and harm yourself. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Things at the very beginning should have warranted your reconsideration. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Family planning in Linyi ranked at the bottom in the entire province. </seg>
<seg id="20"> It was understandable that you felt somewhat worried as a municipal party committee secretary. </seg>
<seg id="21"> However, you were wrong to think that people in Linyi are so crude that force must be used to implement the national law and policy. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Whose fault was it if citizens did not cooperate with the government's action? </seg>
<seg id="23"> Was it because citizens were crude or because the government has a poor public credibility as a result of its numerous lies and tricks over a long period of time? </seg>
<seg id="24"> If the same action by the government ten years ago did not appear that absurd, don't you think your barbarous action was way out of line in 2005 when the Chinese society had achieved remarkable progress and when the human rights protection had been written into the Constitution? </seg>
<seg id="25"> Why don't you reexamine yourself as to how it was that your Linyi alone dare do such things? </seg>
<seg id="26"> How could it be that your Linyi alone could not implement the law using the means of democratic rule of law? </seg>
<seg id="27"> After Chen Guangcheng and a number of brave citizens reported the truth about the barbarous way of implementing the law, after Teng Biao and a number of legal professionals daring to safeguard citizens' rights got involved, and after the National Family Planning Commission made the conclusion of the investigation, Linyi should have offered a sincere explanation to gain the understanding of the public. </seg>
<seg id="28"> After all, family planning is a tough subject with Chinese characteristics. </seg>
<seg id="29"> People could also have understood your difficulties. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Yet, you people instead adopted an absurd move - catching Chen Guangcheng in Beijing and bringing him back to be locked up.  You even attempted to incriminate him in the name of illegally supplying state secret intelligence. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Don't you think this criminal charge very absurd for a blind person living in a poor mountain village? </seg>
<seg id="32"> In fact, as long as you people have really corrected your mistakes and as long as you people have done a good job, would you be afraid of the criticism by a blind person? </seg>
<seg id="33"> Would you people find it necessary to dispatch tens of people to watch him 24 hours a day and even feel so exasperated as to convict him? </seg>
<seg id="34"> On October 4, 2005, Attorney Li Fangping and I went to Dongshigu Village.  We made our position very clear and hoped to resolve the contradiction. </seg>
<seg id="35"> We proposed that we could talk with your officials first to find out what idea and request you people had. </seg>
<seg id="36"> We offered to help you persuade Chen Guangcheng not to make certain remarks. </seg>
<seg id="37"> It was our hope that you people should not treat a blind person this way and that both sides should make some concessions. </seg>
<seg id="38"> However, your policy makers were bent on having your way, and furthermore, even "masterminded" an incident of beating and illegally detaining us. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Do you think you can scare us this way? </seg>
<seg id="40"> We have not done anything illegal. </seg>
<seg id="41"> We are not afraid of anything. </seg>
<seg id="42"> Although the rule of law in China is imperfect, it is not so bad as to allow lawlessness. </seg>
<seg id="43"> If you think you can scare us by using the tricks of hooligans in the underground society, then you have far underestimated our resolution and willpower. </seg>
<seg id="44"> As long as we want, we have many people who have many lawful reasons to go to Linyi or visit Chen Guangcheng. </seg>
<seg id="45"> You can beat attorneys and scholars once, twice, and three times.  Each time there will be widespread attention and coverage. </seg>
<seg id="46"> Do you people dare to beat us ten times? </seg>
<seg id="47"> Don't you care very much about your official position? </seg>
<seg id="48"> In case someone is injured by beating, is your position really that secure? </seg>
<seg id="49"> Playing some lowly tricks of hooligans instead of listening to our reasonable advice, don't you think this is not only foolish but also risky? </seg>
<seg id="50"> I want to tell you clearly that in China there is a large number of excellent citizens who follow their conscience and abide by the rule of law. </seg>
<seg id="51"> We are not afraid of hooligans and the underground society. </seg>
<seg id="52"> We cannot tolerate the reckless trampling of the bottom line of human civilization. </seg>
<seg id="53"> If you are going to the extreme, we will go toward your batons and sticks with confidence and ease in groups and by turns until the moment you retreat. </seg>
<seg id="54"> You should know clearly that using the tricks of hooligans in the underground society will not be of any good to you. </seg>
<seg id="55"> Don't think you can extricate yourself from those local ruffians and hooligans who beat up villagers as long as you stay behind the scenes. </seg>
<seg id="56"> Finally, I also want to remind you to treat Chen Guangcheng well. </seg>
<seg id="57"> Blind since a child, he graduated from a college of traditional medicine and taught himself law and English.  He once sued the Beijing subway company in the interest of the blind people, and he introduced running water for the villagers.  He is known far and wide as "Attorney Chen." </seg>
<seg id="58"> You people went so far as to have shameless villains create rumors online slandering him and even attempted to convict him of a crime of supplying confidential intelligence illegally to overseas recipients.  Don't you think you have gone too far by doing that? </seg>
<seg id="59"> It is illegal for you people to put Chen Guangcheng under house arrest.  It is also risky to you. </seg>
<seg id="60"> Originally, you people could have released him with no trouble. </seg>
<seg id="61"> Since the barbarous implementation of the law has stopped, how long will he go on criticizing if left unchecked? </seg>
<seg id="62"> But, you people are now continuing to smear your own image. </seg>
<seg id="63"> As long as Cheng Guangcheng is not free, you people will never have peace. </seg>
<seg id="64"> You people have tortured him enough. </seg>
<seg id="65"> If you even want to convict him or resort to further hooliganism, we will never look on with folded arms. </seg>
<seg id="66"> Citizen Xu Zhiyong  February 8, 2006 </seg>
</doc>
