<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_a6b18a4b27644df8_CMN_20060215_083500" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chf">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Dalai's Special Envoys Meet with Chinese Officials behind Closed Doors </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> CGP Beili </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dalai's special envoys meet with Chinese officials behind closed doors. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The Dalai Lama stressed that he wants autonomy, not independence, for Tibet. </seg>
<seg id="5"> The special envoys of the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader in exile, are having closed-door meetings with Chinese officials in Beijing with no details released. </seg>
<seg id="6"> This is the fifth official meeting between China and the Dalai's government-in-exile since contacts resumed in 2002. </seg>
<seg id="7"> However, as always, the two sides met behind close doors with no details revealed. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Reporters said that the two sides held talks several times but so far no substantive results have been achieved. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The Dalai Lama, who is in exile in northern India, said that he wants autonomy, not independence, for Tibet. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The Chinese side refused to comment on the bilateral talks. </seg>
<seg id="11"> However, analysts said that Beijing wanted to have the dialogue partly because it is worried that Tibetans' dissatisfaction with the Chinese rule may escalate should this 70-year-old spiritual leader in exile die. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Cultural Identity </seg>
<seg id="13"> The delegation of Dalai's government-in-exile was led by Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari, who was also chief representative to several previous talks. </seg>
<seg id="14"> A spokesperson for the Tibetan government-in-exile said that the several rounds of talks they had with Chinese officials in Switzerland in 2005 were very "close and frank," bringing hopes for Tibetans. </seg>
<seg id="15"> The spokesperson said that their ultimate hope is to resolve the relevant issues on the basis reached through negotiation with the Chinese leadership so that Tibetans will have the freedom to preserve their cultural identity, which they consider important. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="16"> CGP Beili </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="17"> Dalai Lama's Special Envoys Reiterate they do not Seek Tibet's Independence. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The Dalai Lama will go to visit Washington this month. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Prior to the Tibetan spiritual leader Dalai Lama's visit to the United States on November 8, his special envoys said that the Tibetan government-in-exile would not demand for Tibet's independence. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said in Washington that he hoped the Chinese government would indeed preserve Tibet's unique culture and tradition. </seg>
<seg id="21"> During his visit to the US next week, the Dalai Lama is expected to discuss the Tibetan issue with President Bush in hopes that Bush can urge the Chinese government to give Tibet genuine autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Dalai's representative had direct contact with Beijing officials for the first time in Berne in July of this year. </seg>
<seg id="23"> "Genuine Autonomy" </seg>
<seg id="24"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari noted that in recent years the Tibetan government-in-exile has seen some positive aspects when meeting with Chinese authorities. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Dalai Lama's special envoys found that Beijing leaders, especially the representatives from the United Front Work Department of the CPC Central Committee, were more willing than before to hear their opinions. </seg>
<seg id="26"> However, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that the Tibetan government-in-exile still has too many disagreements with the Chinese government and that there is a very big difference between the positions of the two sides. </seg>
<seg id="27"> He said that during the past five years the Tibetan government-in-exile has tried its best to meet the Chinese request for creating a good negotiation environment. </seg>
<seg id="28"> China should also create a good environment for negotiations on the Tibetan issue instead of suppressing the Dalai Lama unrelentingly. </seg>
<seg id="29"> He said that the Dalai Lama does not demand independence for Tibet.  Tibet is still part of China, but the Chinese government must preserve Tibet's unique culture so that "Tibetans will have genuine autonomy." </seg>
<seg id="30"> In addition, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari noted that some Chinese think the Tibetan issue will disappear once the Dalai Lama dies. </seg>
<seg id="31"> He said that this idea is very dangerous because China will lose a historic opportunity to solve the Tibetan issue once the Dalai Lama passes away. </seg>
<seg id="32"> He said that as long as the Chinese government responds to the requests of the Dalai Lama and proposes a final resolution, the Dalai Lama will not need to talk about the Tibetan issue internationally. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b07aeae684cbc1b7_CMN_20060209_051800" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chf">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Negotiation And Compromise are Important Democratic Methods! (ZT) </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Houze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I just saw a post by a net friend on The Great Spirit: To Old Mr. Guiren. </seg>
<seg id="4"> His/her original words were "negotiation and compromise are important democratic methods, or else, splitting because of disagreements is the failure of democracy!!!  I hope idealistic democrats will pay full attention to this point!" </seg>
<seg id="5"> This bland remark that has not roused interest among any net friends led me to indulge in a train of thought while all sorts of feelings welled up in my mind. </seg>
<seg id="6"> At this time, I thought of ancient China as well as the past of the West. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Seldom posting topics, I could not help replying to the post of this net friend in the form of a topic post. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Let's take a look first at ancient China. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Everybody knows that beginning with the First Qin Emperor, China has constructed a large and unified centralized power system, with all dynasties that followed operating under this political framework. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Although a "double-track system" was temporarily implemented in the Han Dynasty, that is, a political system consisting of a dual coexisting feudal system and centralized power system, after all, there was still a centralized power system in the end. </seg>
<seg id="11"> The effect of this kind of centralized power system under the conditions at that time in history had its progressive side, had its aspect of promoting the development of forces of production. </seg>
<seg id="12"> However, we should also see that the prolonged period of more than 2,000 years of running this system resulted in a lack of creativity, initiative, and activity in local areas, making it even less possible to formulate, based on local conditions, various kinds of regulations and policies appropriate for local development. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The pyramid-like system of government also caused lower-level officials to only look upward, following every detail of orders from higher levels. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Since all local officials in the county government were appointed by the central government, they had no room for coordination and negotiation among themselves, let alone with those ordinary citizens. </seg>
<seg id="15"> When their rights were infringed upon, peasants in ancient China could do nothing but put up with it time and again. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Only when their most basic rights were threatened, that is, when their rights of existence were deprived by widespread famine, tyranny, and natural disasters, would they rise in revolt with sharpened sticks. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Over 2,000 years, several peasant uprisings spread like storms across the country, from the spontaneous Chen Sheng Wu Guang Uprising to the plotted Yellow Turban Uprising, to the Huang Chao Riot in the Tang Dynasty, as well as the one-month dynastic rule as a result of Li Zicheng's uprising.  Except for Zhu Yuanzhang, none achieved victory in the true sense of the word. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Even the Ming Dynasty established this way by Zhu Yuanzhang was still nothing but a rotating replacement of other dynasties, with no change in the system. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Born a commoner with little education, Zhu Yuanzhang implemented ancient China's centralized power system to a sickening extreme.  The brimming vitality characteristic of the Tang Dynasty, born of openness, freedom, and tolerance, was replaced by stagnant lifelessness. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The free speech atmosphere vanished from the land of China for some time. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Human nature suffered utmost suppression. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Everyone became overcautious and dared not talk too much, from fear and trepidation. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The result of this sole successful peasant uprising over 2,000 years turned the Chinese people into subhuman beings for a period of time. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Now let's take a look at the Middle Ages in Western Europe, known as the Dark Ages. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Middle Ages in Western Europe was a period of one thousand years which came about after Western Rome was destroyed by nomads and had nothing to do with the previous ancient Greece and Rome. </seg>
<seg id="26"> This period was characterized by fiefdoms, namely land fiefdoms. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Landlords at lower levels had more independent power. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Whether they were small feudal lords with territories extending a few kilometers or the nobility of dukes, marquises, counts, viscounts, and barons who appeared on formal occasions, as people of various ranks were able to mutually check and balance and depend on one another, with the conditions and abilities to fight for their legitimate rights from the king, there were scenes of kings and noblemen sitting together for negotiations of their own respective interests, scenes never seen in ancient Chinese history. </seg>
<seg id="29"> They made mutual compromises and concessions instead of overthrowing or superseding other parties by using force. </seg>
<seg id="30"> This way, by means of various kinds of contracts, rights were continuously granted to noblemen and commoners, and with increasing power for noblemen and commoners, the king's rights became increasingly diminished. </seg>
<seg id="31"> In the end, the British queen became only ceremonial, with no actual power. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Democracy was gradually realized through this method! </seg>
<seg id="33"> Let's come back to make a comparison with ancient China, with all power centralized in the hands of the emperor (except for Li Shimin) and with almost no noblemen.  It would be hard for peasants to sit with the king at the negotiating table over a cup of tea and a glass of wine, making mutual compromises and concessions in a relaxed and pleasant manner and formulating contracts to the satisfaction of the two sides. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Under such circumstances, when the right of existence was deprived, the only way remaining was to overthrow the existing dynasty by force and try to replace it. </seg>
<seg id="35"> Consequently, there was a repeated rotation, from the heyday of the Tang Dynasty to the morbidity of the Ming Dynasty. </seg>
<seg id="36"> Comparing Chinese history with Western history, we find there seems to be no Western country where conflict between the ruler and the ruled was as aggravated as it was in ancient China. </seg>
<seg id="37"> In no Western country were peasant uprisings as frequent as in ancient China. </seg>
<seg id="38"> In Western countries, when conflicts between ancient royal households and peasants arose, noblemen and commoners would first think of achieving resolution through negotiations to protect their own interests.  They would make some mutual concessions to gradually win more rights, while force was rarely used. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Understanding this, you will see that even as we enter the 21st century, some democratic "fighters" on the internet, having inherited the idea of the ultra, absolute totalitarian system of the Ming Dynasty, </seg>
<seg id="40"> and also because their bodies are eroded by the poison of the Cultural Revolution, these democratic "fighters" can talk about nothing except annihilation and overthrow. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Yet it is this kind of ideology that is the largest obstacle to democracy, because these people don't understand that negotiation, consultation, and compromise are the most important methods and approaches for realizing democracy. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b1314fab782e7592_CMN_20060209_044700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chf">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Cao Xiaoming: Who Foots Bill for Enriching Rural Cultural Activities? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Houze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> This Spring Festival, this writer was lucky enough to spend the holiday in rural China and visit some relatives and friends. </seg>
<seg id="4"> While impressed by the rich festive atmosphere in rural China, I was also concerned with the drab cultural activities in the countryside. </seg>
<seg id="5"> This writer found in one village with friends and relatives that previously at Spring Festival each year, this village would spontaneously organize villagers to put on a local theatrical show called "Revolving Lantern." </seg>
<seg id="6"> Both adults and children could play roles in this show based on characters in the Three Warring Kingdoms.  The villagers never grew tired of watching it. </seg>
<seg id="7"> There were several performing teams for "Revolving Lantern" across the township.  They not only performed in their own villages but also visited other villages, creating liveliness through their exchanges. </seg>
<seg id="8"> However, this year this village no longer organized it. </seg>
<seg id="9"> It turned out that a large sum of money was needed for purchasing costumes alone for "Revolving Lantern."  In the past, costumes were bought through fund raising among the villagers, yet they are now too worn out to wear. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Asking villagers door to door for money again, nobody wanted to do it.  Similar situations also occurred in several other villages across the township. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Without the "Revolving Lantern," the village suddenly became cold and cheerless. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Adults started to play mahjong. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Children also started to play poker. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Villagers all said there was nothing going on for this New Year festival. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Setting off firecrackers or playing mahjong has now become one of the major features of the New Year celebration in rural areas. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Meanwhile, gambling persists in spite of numerous bans and is tending to spread further.  Winning or losing as much as 10,000 yuan in a single game has even become commonplace.  In particular, a large number of peasants returning from their migrant jobs outside have become major players at gambling houses. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Their money earned by their own sweat over a whole year thereby goes down the drain. </seg>
<seg id="18"> In addition, gambling-related family disputes frequently occur.  Some even lead to tragedies of divorce and death. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Some peasants say they gamble not only during the New Year festival, but also frequently participate in gambling during the slack season. </seg>
<seg id="20"> There is no place to go if they don't gamble. </seg>
<seg id="21"> It is too difficult to organize some cultural activities, to find some fun in rural areas. </seg>
<seg id="22"> There are neither facilities nor funds, but also there are no people acting as organizers. </seg>
<seg id="23"> However, in this regard, what Jiangxi has done is doubtlessly good news for peasants. </seg>
<seg id="24"> In order to enrich the cultural life of the peasant population, the Jiangxi provincial government, starting in September of last year, not only implemented "theatrical performances funded by the government, operated by the market, supported by townships, provided for peasant enjoyment," </seg>
<seg id="25"> but is also allocating at least 60 million yuan annually to a special fund for rural cultural enterprises, so as to bring high-quality cultural products to the rural population. </seg>
<seg id="26"> At the start of the new year, 10 million yuan was again added, bringing the total amount to 100 million yuan for the establishment of the special fund for rural cultural enterprise. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Moreover, the "bills" paid with this special fund are for real benefits: </seg>
<seg id="28"> inviting various kinds of professional artistic troupes to stage performances in rural areas, with at least four performances per year in each township; </seg>
<seg id="29"> inviting various movie theater companies to dispatch teams to put on movies in rural areas, with at least six dramas and educational science movies per year in each administrative village; </seg>
<seg id="30"> organizing and carrying out mass cultural activities with local characteristics, with at least 2-3 events per year in each township. </seg>
<seg id="31"> From this "purchase inventory list," it is easy for us to see that the government is not simply providing funds, but trying its best to think about how to use the limited funding to provide what is most needed and to bring value-added cultural enjoyment for the vast rural population.  It has done a real job. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Currently, the vast numbers of peasants are rejoicing about being exempt from paying grain tax to the government. </seg>
<seg id="33"> If the government can do what Jiangxi did to "foot the bill" for enriching rural people's cultural activities, it will be another joy from heaven for peasants. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Furthermore, this "joy" will not only get peasants away from the mahjong table but also get them "active" in cultural activities, which helps add contributions to the construction of new socialist rural areas. </seg>
</doc>
