<doc docid="CCTV4_NEWS3_CMN_20060216_075800_208_476.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chg">
<seg id="1"> Good. Thank you for tuning in to China's News. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The Chinese Consulate General in Karachi confirmed on the 15th that three Chinese engineers and a Pakistani driver were murdered yesterday in Balochistan province in southwestern Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="3"> After learning the news late last night, Chinese President Hu Jintao showed deep concern for the safety of the Chinese engineers in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="4"> He instructed the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Chinese embassy and consulates in Pakistan to demand that Pakistan arrest the murderers, to ensure the safety of the Chinese there, and to properly handle the aftermath of the victims. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Hu Jintao also extended his condolences to the Chinese victims and expressed sincere sympathy for the victims' families. </seg>
<seg id="6"> Early this morning, Li Zhaoxing, Chinese Foreign Minister, made an urgent call to his Pakistani counterpart Kasuri, under the instruction of President Hu Jintao. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The Chinese embassy and consulates in Pakistan immediately mobilized an emergency plan, and relevant personnel had already arrived at the scene. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Premier Wen Jiabao had also given instructions to ensure the safety of the Chinese personnel, to properly handle the aftermath, and to request Pakistan to arrest the murderers. </seg>
<seg id="9"> In addition, according to the newest information from the Chinese Consulate General in Karachi, the bodies of the three Chinese had been transported to Karachi early this morning and will be brought back to China on a chartered flight within a few days. </seg>
<seg id="10"> After the attack, the Chinese Consulate General in Karachi immediately dispatched a three-person team to rush to the scene, and transported the bodies of the three Chinese engineers to be placed in a Karachi hospital. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Meanwhile, more than 10 Chinese personnel who work at the same work site with these few people had retreated to Karachi. They are emotionally stable at the moment. </seg>
<seg id="12"> The attack happened in the town of Hub, southeast of Quetta. </seg>
<seg id="13"> On that day, six Chinese engineers who worked at a local cement factory were in a car returning to their residences from their work site. Their car was suddenly stopped by some unidentified gunmen on motorcycles. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The gunmen opened fire with assault rifles, killing three engineers. </seg>
<seg id="15"> After the attack, a tribal militant group named the Baloch Liberation Army claimed responsibility for the shooting. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Pakistan's Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement that night, strongly condemning the attack, calling the incident a terrorist act. </seg>
<seg id="17"> The three Chinese killed were Long Hongbao, Wei Jianping, and Zhao Bin. They were engineers from the Hefei Cement Industry Design and Research Institute of Anhui under the Headquarters of the China National Building Material Group Corporation. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Qin Gang, Spokesman for China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, stated today that Chinese leaders were greatly concerned about the attack on Chinese engineers in Pakistan. They requested Pakistan to ensure the safety of the Chinese personnel there, and to arrest the murderers as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Qin Gang said that Zhang Chunxiang, Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan, had related the relevant situation and lodged negotiations with Pakistani government and army leaders. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Pakistan strongly condemned this barbarous and cruel incident and expressed their condolences to the victims. They also indicated that they will do their utmost to arrest the murderers and will fully coordinate with China in handling the matter. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is coordinating relevant departments to arrange to bring back the victims' bodies to China as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id="22"> The aftermath handling team formed by the victims' work unit, the Hefei Cement Industry Design and Research Institute of Anhui under the Headquarters of the China National Building Material Group Corporation, had left Beijing for Pakistan this morning. </seg>
<seg id="23"> China's Ministry of Commerce had also set up an emergency task force after the incident. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Chen Jian, Assistant Minister of Commerce, said that if work safety cannot be guaranteed for the time being, the project at the cement factory will not resume. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Only when the safety of the workers is guaranteed will they continue with the project. </seg>
<seg id="26"> After the forming of the ((emergency)) task force, we immediately, er, instructed the frontline personnel to rush to the scene to investigate the local situation. </seg>
<seg id="27"> We also confirmed the identities of the victims within the shortest time in China. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Chen Jian claimed that the Ministry of Commerce will follow the handling of the incident closely and will actively coordinate the handling of the aftermath among relevant units. </seg>
<seg id="29"> If work safety cannot be guaranteed, we would request the Chinese enterprise to stop its work. </seg>
<seg id="30"> We will resume work only after the work safety is truly guaranteed. </seg>
<seg id="31"> The Attock B Line Cement Factory project was launched in 2004. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The Hefei Cement Industry Design and Research Institute is responsible for providing all the equipments and technical support for the cement factory. The project is expected to finish in the first half of 2006. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="CCTV4_NEWS3_CMN_20060217_075800_447_833.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chg">
<seg id="1"> The bodies of the three Chinese engineers killed in the attack in Pakistan were flown back to China from Karachi on a Pakistani air force chartered flight at 7 a.m. local time today. </seg>
<seg id="2"> Let us watch the report sent back by Tao Ye, our reporter who traveled to Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="3"> The bodies of the three Chinese engineers killed near Karachi, Pakistan, on the 15th were transported back to China from the Karachi Faisal Air Force Base in Pakistan on the early morning of the 17th. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The atmosphere at the Karachi Faisal Air Force Base in the early morning was solemn. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Zhang Chunxiang, China's Ambassador to Pakistan; the Interior Minister of the Province of Sindh where Karachi is located; and Sun Chunye, China's Consul General to Pakistan, led employees at China's embassy and consulates in Pakistan and workers of the Chinese company to bid their last farewell to their deceased compatriots. </seg>
<seg id="6"> All the people at the scene, led by Ambassador Zhang Chunxiang, bowed to the three coffins three times. </seg>
<seg id="7"> After that, soldiers from the Pakistani honor guard slowly lifted the three coffins onto the chartered flight provided by Pakistan. </seg>
