<seg id="14"> Japan's Cabinet Office announced the fourth-quarter Gross Domestic Product information for 2005 on Friday. </seg>
<seg id="15"> After price adjustments, the actual increase in the quarter from October to December had increased by 1.4 percent compared to the last quarter, higher than the 1.2 percent expected. </seg>
<seg id="16"> The main factors were the strong domestic demand and the growth in exports to major countries such as China and the United States. It had shown a sign of continuous economic recovery. </seg>
<seg id="17"> This was the fourth consecutive quarter that Japan had showed an economic growth, and the largest since the first to the third quarter in 2005. It was mainly because of the help from personal expenditures, capital expenditures, and steady exports. </seg>
<seg id="18"> In addition, Japan's Central Bank will also terminate its five-year-long extremely relaxed monetary policy in April, thus fostering an expectation for an economic boom in the financial market. </seg>
<seg id="19"> With the slight improvement in the unemployment rate and wages from October to December, private consumption had increased by 0.8 percent. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The Nikkei Index rose after the release of the GDP information. However, by morning closing it had dropped 0.74 percent. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The Japanese yen fell after a short appreciation. The trading price lingered at around 118.15 Japanese yen to 1 U.S. dollar. </seg>
