<seg id="14"> On Friday, Japan's Cabinet Office released GDP data for the 4th quarter of 2005. </seg>
<seg id="15"> After price adjustment, actual growth in GDP in the October-December quarter was up 1.4% from the previous quarter, registering a growth rate that was 1.2% higher than expected. </seg>
<seg id="16"> The primary reasons are strong domestic demand and rising exports to major countries, such as China and the United States. This is a sign of a sustained economic recovery. </seg>
<seg id="17"> This is the fourth quarter in a row that Japan has witnessed economic growth and the highest growth rate since the first and third quarters of 2005. It is primarily due to individual spending, capital expenditure and strong exports. </seg>
<seg id="18"> In addition, Japan's central bank will end in April its  extremely loose currency policy of the past five years, thereby encouraging the financial market's expectations for an economic upturn. </seg>
<seg id="19"> In October through December, nongovernmental consumption increased by 0.8% thanks to a moderate improvement in the unemployment rate and wages. </seg>
