<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> A Mother Ten Years in the Past </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Helen Li </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I saw this article and decided to share it with you; </seg>
<seg id="4"> This is not a momentary impulse, but rather a warm kindheartedness that has long existed in the heart. </seg>
<seg id="5"> I asked myself what I would do if it were me. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The answer is very clear. I would way, "You have the wrong number" and hang up the telephone. </seg>
<seg id="7"> I've been thinking all this year about how one can actually help someone. </seg>
<seg id="8"> I have already given up on actions such as donating money or goods. </seg>
<seg id="9"> A couple days ago a friend said, "I already have no spare time to take care of myself. As for helping people, the heart is there by the means are not." </seg>
<seg id="10"> Have a nice day :) </seg>
<seg id="11"> Helen </seg>
<seg id="12"> A Mother Ten Years in the Past </seg>
<seg id="13"> It was a day ten years ago. The teacher was using the lunch break to nap at home, when suddenly the telephone rang. </seg>
<seg id="14"> She answered and heard an unfamiliar rough voice from the receiver: "Your child stole a book and we caught her. Come over right away!" </seg>
<seg id="15"> The crying of a little girl could also be heard though the receiver, as well as the sound of somebody nearby scolding her. </seg>
<seg id="16"> She turned her head to look at her only daughter watching the television and then immediately understood what was happening. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Clearly, a little girl had been caught by a store clerk stealing a book and did not want her family to find out, so she dialed a number at random and happened to call there. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Of course, she could hang up and forget about it, or even reprimand the party on the other line, </seg>
<seg id="19"> because this affair had absolutely nothing to do with her. </seg>
<seg id="20"> But she was a teacher, and it could be that it was one of her students. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Through the telephone, she could roughly imagine that the little girl who had made a mistake on the spur of the moment was surely terrified, since she was facing what could be life's most frightening circumstance. </seg>
<seg id="22"> After hesitating a moment, a thought suddenly came to her mind. Yes, she would do it. </seg>
<seg id="23"> Thereupon, after asking the bookstore's address, she rushed over there. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Just as she had anticipated, standing in the bookstore was a little girl with a face full of tears. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The adults beside her were ferociously and loudly scolding her. </seg>
<seg id="26"> She instantly rushed forward and gathered the pitiful little girl into her arms, then turned toward the nearby store clerk and said: "Whatever you have to say you can say to me. You shouldn't frighten children." </seg>
<seg id="27"> During the muttering of the somewhat unwilling store clerk, she paid the fine of less than one hundred yuan and then, with the little girl in hand, walked out of the store where she could see clearly the face overwhelmed by panic and tears. </seg>
<seg id="28"> She smiled and returned home with the little girl where she tidied her up without asking anything, then let the little girl leave, </seg>
<seg id="29"> As the little girl was about to go, she also made a point of urging, "If you want to read a book, then come here to Auntie's house. There are lots of books here.' </seg>
<seg id="30"> The still badly shaken little girl looked are her deeply for a moment, then dashed off, after which she never came back. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Time rushed by like running water. Imperceptibly, ten years went by in a flash. </seg>
<seg id="32"> She had forgotten the incident, still living there as before, she led a calm and peaceful life. </seg>
<seg id="33"> One afternoon, there was a knocking on the outside door. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Opening the door to her apartment, she saw a pretty young woman she did not know. The girl was smiling broadly and in her hands she held a stack of presents. </seg>
<seg id="35"> "Who are you looking for?" </seg>
<seg id="36"> she asked with uncertainty. </seg>
<seg id="37"> The young girl excitedly gave a long explanation. </seg>
<seg id="38"> To her surprise, from the unfamiliar young lady's story she suddenly realized that the young woman was actually the little girl from that year. Ten years later, she had graduated from university without difficulty and had now come especially to call on her. </seg>
<seg id="39"> The young woman's eyes glistened with tears as she said in a gentle voice: "Although I still don't understand even today why you were willing to pass yourself off as my mother and come to my rescue, but for the last ten years I had a constant feeling that I wanted to cry out 'Mother' to you." </seg>
<seg id="40"> The teacher's eyes started to cloud over as well. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Somewhat curious, she asked: "If I hadn't helped you that day, what would have been the result?" </seg>
<seg id="42"> The young woman's face instantly darkened and she lightly shook her head, saying: "I'm not sure. Maybe I would have gone on doing stupid things, or I might even have died." </seg>
<seg id="43"> A violent shiver went through the teacher's heart, then she rejoiced to  herself. </seg>
<seg id="44"> The impetuous decision that she had made back then had unexpectedly had such an influence on a person's entire life. </seg>
<seg id="45"> Looking at the happy smile on the young woman's face, she also began to smile. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="46"> <POSTER>  zhang xiwen </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="47"> While the world is full of lies and cheating that fill the air like junk messages, Buddha says, "Who would enter hell but I would enter it..." </seg>
<seg id="48"> Whoever is willing to do that, I congratulate him. He will achieve Buddhahood sooner. </seg>
<seg id="49"> Human nature is good at the outset. </seg>
<seg id="50"> Everybody has a compassionate heart. </seg>
<seg id="51"> The world is going to the dogs and people's hearts have changed. </seg>
<seg id="52"> Perhaps only by abandoning one's own Buddha can one do a little good. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_goodarticles_90837c9a1fbe858e_CMN_20060214_082900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Military Observation: How Long Can Iran Hold Out under US Air Attacks? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Yun Feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> If we describe conventional war of attrition as causing the opponent to bleed to death, then from the outset modern warfare consists of shooting a gun toward the opponent's head in order to render him a "vegetable" even before there is time to bleed. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The disparity between the military capabilities of Iran and the US is not one of quantity, but rather in the understanding of modern war. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Iran, which fought a victorless eight-year war with Iraq, seems not yet to have understood the true significance of modern hi-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="6"> Following an analysis of US military deployments, Britain's "International Intelligence--Commentary" recently said that the US military is carrying out preparations to launch a large scale air assault on Iran...... </seg>
<seg id="7"> The current status of Iran's air force is cause for concern. </seg>
<seg id="8"> The present situation of Iran's air force is quite similar to that of Iraq's air force prior to the 2003 war. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The country does not possess the capacity to research and develop modern weapons on its own and is also under an arms embargo imposed by the west. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Once war breaks out, it is uncertain whether the antiquated planes in Iran's air force will be able to take to the air to engage US forces. </seg>
<seg id="11"> At present, Iran's air-defense system consists primarily of an air force belonging to Iran's regular forces, the land-based air-defense force and the air-defense capacity of the revolutionary guard. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Of these, Iran's air force presently has a manpower of 50,000 and more than 300 aircraft of various models. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The most important aircraft models include US-manufactured F-4 Phantoms, F5 Tigers, F-14 Tomcats and Russian-manufactured Mig-29s. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The land-based air-defense force is primarily equipped with surface-to-air missiles of the US-manufactured Hawk series and the British Rapier series, as well as a portion belong to the Russian-manufactured SAM series. </seg>
<seg id="15"> With regards to the current status of Iran's air-defense strength,  analysis by individuals such as the US military expert Harold Hutchison and  military expert [Hela Muqixin] of the [Russian Political and Military Research Institute] indicates that, viewed from the present situation, there are still holes in Iran's air-defense capabilities and air-defense system. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Hutchison says that with respect to overall capabilities, Iran's air force simply is not on the same level as the US air force. </seg>
<seg id="17"> A large number of the US-manufactured jetfighters that Iran is equipped with cannot be used because of a lack of spare parts and upgrading. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The F-14 fighter was once the trump card of Iran's air force, but today there are only ten or so that are able to fly. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The dependability in actual combat of the AIM-54 Phoenix missiles they carry, known for their ultra-long distance attack capabilities, is also doubtful. </seg>
<seg id="20"> [Hela Muqixin] points out however that the air-defense missile systems provided to Iran by the US in the 1970s and 1980s have lost their warfare capabilities because of a lack of spare parts. </seg>
<seg id="21"> In addition, the other non-systematic air-defense weapons obtained from Russia and other countries are simply incapable of countering US forces possessing powerful electromagnetic countermeasure capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Scraping Together a Military Affects Battle Capability </seg>
<seg id="23"> Clearly, Iran's government is also aware that its fate in a conflict depends upon whether it can defend the sky above and it has been carrying out eleventh-hour preparations by scraping together whatever it can find in order to build up its air-defense system. </seg>
<seg id="24"> At present, its methods can be summarized into two devices: </seg>
<seg id="25"> The first is an all-out effort to conceal key nuclear facilities and beef up their defense capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="26"> According to a report in the British newspaper The Times, Iran has hidden the Natanz Nuclear Facility, the Isfahan Uranium Enrichment Center and other core components of their nuclear facilities eighteen meters underground and added a two-meter thick concrete protection shell. </seg>
<seg id="27"> But the US military is one step ahead. As early as the 1991 Persian Gulf War, it saw the effectiveness of underground bunkers in anti-aircraft defense and rushed to develop various types of earth-penetrating bombs. </seg>
<seg id="28"> After ten years of focused research, the US military has a full complement of strategies and weapons to counter reinforced underground bunkers. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Iran has recently also bought a large amount of advanced air-defense weapons from Russia. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Since the end of last year, Iran's government has reached a series of agreements with Russia to purchase Pechora-2A air defense missile systems as well as 29 Tor-M1 air-defense missile systems valued at US$700m. </seg>
<seg id="31"> However, modern warfare is a contest of system against system. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The various air-attack weapons of the US military have all been developed by the country itself for its own benefit and, through many years of perfectioning in actual combat, they have been molded into an impressive war machine. </seg>
<seg id="33"> On the other hand, Iran's "up-to-date weapons" have been scraped together from other countries. Whether or not they can be made combat effective in such a short time is still in question. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Iran's Lags Behind Not Only in Weapons </seg>
<seg id="35"> The concept of "air-land battle" was first raised in "Operations", published by the US military in 1982. It stresses reliance on strength in the air to carry out attacks against the enemy's strategically valuable targets. This paralyses the other side's command systems at the start of the war and turns the enemy's conventional forces, even if they are superior, into a "slab of meat on a cutting board." </seg>
<seg id="36"> In the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the 1999 Kosovo War and the 2003 Iraq War, the US military did not concern itself with how many planes the opponent had, but rather the range of its own Tomahawk cruise missiles. </seg>
<seg id="37"> Even if Iran's government has prepared for a possible air attack and has begun to take steps to reinforce its air-defense capabilities, Iran, which fought to a stalemate in an eight-year war with Iraq, seems not to have fully understood the true meaning of modern hi-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="38"> With the progress of the US military's military transformation in recent years, the US military's air-attack operations are completely different from the carpet bombing of the Vietnam War and instead rely on full-depth air assaults with various hi-tech weapons and modern information technology. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Faced with this kind of air assault, how long Iran's land-based air defense systems can hold out is an unknown. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Source: CRI Online- "World News Journal" </seg>
<seg id="41"> There are no big issues in Quanda's eyes.  All issues in the world are common issues. </seg>
<seg id="42"> Quanda Forum:  http://hwz.1--0.net </seg>
<seg id="43"> Email replies will automatically be posted in the forum. </seg>
<seg id="44"> Quanda comments...... </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_goodarticles_f1009483f7a289df_CMN_20060208_091400" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Joining Hands with Google to Battle Microsoft: Will Dell Charge Microsoft "Top-Shelf Fees"? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Yun Feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dell Inc. (US: DELL) and Google confirmed on Tuesday that Dell is currently testing PCs installed with Google's software pack. </seg>
<seg id="4"> This step could form a significant threat to Microsoft's (MicrosoftCorp., MSFT) dominant position in the PC software market. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Dell spokesman Jess Blackburn said the company is currently evaluating Google's software. </seg>
<seg id="6"> After the software has been installed, the PC-user will be able to use the software to conduct searches on the Internet as well as search through information stored on the PC. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Blackburn confirmed that the software being evaluated by the company includes a Google-supported Dell homepage, a Google desktop search tool and a Google tool bar. </seg>
<seg id="8"> At the same time, Google spokesman Jon Murchinson also confirmed that the company was working with Dell in testing a software bundle developed by Google. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Earlier, a report in the Wall Street Journal had said that IT upstart Google was in talks with Dell and Hewlett-Packard in an attempt to convince the computer manufacturing giants to install Google software in their computers. </seg>
<seg id="10"> According to an insider quoted by the Wall Street Journal, in order to achieve this end, Google may have to pay up to US$3bn over the next three years. </seg>
<seg id="11"> However, the two companies have not disclosed any relevant details. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Furthermore, HP still refuses to issue a comment. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Microsoft spokesman Neil Charney refused to comment on the above information. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Currently, Microsoft is planning to launch a search tool for the next generation of its Windows operating system and strengthen the development of its online business. </seg>
<seg id="15"> On the day of the news statement, shares in Google fell another 4.46% to US$367.92. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Shares in Microsoft fell that day by 1% to close at US$26.94. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Some analysts say that Google is eagerly seeking to expand in a direction beyond web searching and that linking up with Dell and other PC giants could prompt Google to threaten Microsoft in its core businesses. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Matt Rosoff, analyst with the market research firm Directions on Microsoft, says that Microsoft is unquestionably concerned and worried by Google's eagerness to expand into other sources of revenue. </seg>
<seg id="19"> But other analysts strongly disagree. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Charles Di Bona, analyst with market research firm Sanford C. Bernstein, says that it is still too early to talk about Google shaking Windows' dominate position. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Reporter Handbook: Is Google shaking up Microsoft's landscape? </seg>
<seg id="22"> Hui Zhengyi </seg>
<seg id="23"> Without doubt, the computer has become a necessity in modern man's life and work. </seg>
<seg id="24"> But while everybody has become familiar with operating computers, only a small portion of people understand the working principles behind a computer. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Just like with an "idiot" camera, if the interface is friendly and the software is convenient and quick to use, the vast majority of "newbies" can find their way around the black box that is a computer. </seg>
<seg id="26"> For this reason, the software originally installed by the PC manufacturer more often than not determines the usage habits of most consumers. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Indeed, it was through this measure that Microsoft took firm hold of the market for PC operating systems. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Now, Microsoft's new rival, Google, also intends to use this method to take a piece of the pie. </seg>
<seg id="29"> In regards to this, a well-known organization in the Taiwanese economic media recently made an interesting analogy. </seg>
<seg id="30"> "Dell, HP and other computer manufacturers are starting to treat the computers they produce as supermarket shelves and they are charging 'top shelf fees' to software companies. </seg>
<seg id="31"> The winning bidder can cause its software to appear in the 'crucial ten minutes' after the user turns on the new computer and thereby induce the consumer to use their product. </seg>
<seg id="32"> This type of fee method is like the top-shelve fees charged by supermarkets to food companies." </seg>
<seg id="33"> Without doubt, this phenomenon indicates that Microsoft's control is being shaken. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Microsoft's managers have warned Bill Gates, saying that if Google starts paying money to PC manufacturers in order to have computers shipped with Google software installed, then Microsoft's position as overlord will ultimately be threatened. </seg>
<seg id="35"> Whatever the final outcome, Microsoft's easy days safely perched at the top of the ladder might become history. </seg>
<seg id="36"> After all, keeping a market is much more difficult than creating a market </seg>
<seg id="37"> There are no big issues in Quanda's eyes.  All issues in the world are common issues. </seg>
<seg id="38"> Quanda Forum:  http://hwz.1--0.net </seg>
<seg id="39"> Email replies will automatically be posted in the forum. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Quanda comments:.....Everything is changing. </seg>
