<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Dalai Lama's Envoys Hold Closed Door Talks with Chinese Officials </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Beili of the CGP </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dalai Lama's Envoys Hold Closed Door Talks with Chinese Officials. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Dalai Lama Stressed he Wants Autonomy, Not Independence, for Tibet. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Envoys of Tibet's exiled spiritual leader the Dalai Lama are in China for closed door talks with Chinese officials. Details have not yet been released. </seg>
<seg id="6"> This is the fifth official meeting since China and the Dalai Lama's exiled government resumed contacts in 2002. </seg>
<seg id="7"> But, as in the past, the two sides are meeting behind closed doors. No details have yet been disclosed. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Reporters say the two sides have held talks on several occasions, but so far there have been no tangible results. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The Dalai Lama, who is in exile in Northern India, says he wants autonomy, not independence, for Tibet </seg>
<seg id="10"> China has refused to comment on the talks between the two sides. </seg>
<seg id="11"> But analysts say Beijing wants dialogue, partly because it fears the death of the 70-year-old spiritual leader in exile could lead to heightened sentiments among Tibetans unhappy with China rule. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Cultural Identity </seg>
<seg id="13"> The delegation from the Dalai Lama's exiled government is led by Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari. He was also the lead delegate in earlier talks. </seg>
<seg id="14"> A spokesman for the Tibetan government-in-exile said the round of talks that they had with Chinese officials in Switzerland in 2005 were very "intensive and frank" and this has given the Tibetan people hope. </seg>
<seg id="15"> The spokesman said their ultimate hope is to resolve the relevant issues on the basis of a negotiated settlement with the Chinese leadership so that the Tibetan people will have the freedom to preserve what is important to them, which is their cultural identity. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="16"> <POSTER>  CGP </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="17"> Dalai Lama's Envoy Reiterates Tibetan Independence is Not Being Sought </seg>
<seg id="18"> Dalai Lama to Visit Washington This Month </seg>
<seg id="19"> In the run-up to the Tibetan spiritual leader the Dalai Lama's trip to the US on November 8, his envoy has said that the Tibetan government-in-exile is not seeking Tibet's independence. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said in Washington that he hopes that the Chinese government will truly protect Tibet's unique culture and traditions. </seg>
<seg id="21"> It is expected that during his visit to the US next week the Dalai Lama will discuss the Tibet issue with President Bush in the hope that Bush will press the Chinese government to give Tibet genuine autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="22"> In July of this year, envoys of the Dalai Lama's met with Beijing's officials in Berne for their first direct contact. </seg>
<seg id="23"> "Genuine Autonomy" </seg>
<seg id="24"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that in recent years talks between the Tibetan government-in-exile and the Chinese authorities has revealed some positive elements. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The envoys of the Dalai Lama found that the leaders in Beijing, particularly the delegates of the CCP's United Front Work Department, are more willing than in the past to listen to their opinions. </seg>
<seg id="26"> But Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said the Tibetan government-in-exile and the Chinese government still have several differences of opinion and are still far-apart in their standpoints. </seg>
<seg id="27"> He said that in the last five years the Tibetan government-in-exile has done its utmost to respond to China's demands in order to create a favorable negotiating environment. </seg>
<seg id="28"> In order to create a favorable negotiating environment on the Tibetan issue, China should refrain from blindly pressuring the Dalai Lama. </seg>
<seg id="29"> He said the Dalai Lama does not seek independence for Tibet and that Tibet is still a part of China, but that the Chinese government must protect Tibet's unique culture and "allow the Tibetan people genuine autonomy". </seg>
<seg id="30"> Furthermore, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that some Chinese people think that once the Dalai Lama has died the Tibet issue will disappear. </seg>
<seg id="31"> He said that this thinking is extremely dangerous because once the Dalai Lama is dead China will have lost a historic opportunity to solve the Tibet issue. </seg>
<seg id="32"> He said that the Chinese government only needs to respond to the Dalai Lama's demands and suggest a final means of resolution, then the Dalai Lama will no longer need to talk at the international level about the Tibet issue. </seg>
